# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: propelling-nozzle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The **North American A-5 Vigilante** is an American carrier-based supersonic bomber and reconnaissance aircraft designed and built by North American Aviation (NAA) for the United States Navy.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Before the 1962 unification of Navy and Air Force designations, it was designated **A3J**.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Development of the A-5 had started in 1954 as a private venture by NAA, who sought to produce a capable supersonic long-distance bomber as a successor to the abortive North American XA2J Super Savage.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] It was a large and complex aircraft that incorporated several innovative features, such as being the first bomber to feature a digital computer, while its ability to attain speeds of up to Mach 2 while carrying a nuclear strike payload was also relatively ambitious for the era.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The US Navy saw the value of such a bomber, leading to a contract for its full development and production being issued to the firm on 29 August 1956.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The type performed its first flight just over two years later, on 31 August 1958.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The Vigilante was introduced by the US Navy during June 1961; it succeeded the Douglas A-3 Skywarrior as the Navy's primary nuclear strike aircraft, but its service in this capacity was relatively brief due to the deemphasizing of manned bombers in American nuclear strategy.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] A far larger quantity of the RA-5C tactical strike reconnaissance variant were also procured by the service, which saw extensive service during the Vietnam War.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] It also established several world records in both long-distance speed and altitude categories.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] During the mid-1970s, the withdrawal of the type commenced after a relatively short service life, largely due to the aircraft being expensive and complex to operate, as well as being a victim of post-Vietnam military cutbacks.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The late 1940s and early 1950s were marked by a series of fast-paced advancements in the field of aviation.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The aircraft manufacturer North American Aviation (NAA) was one of a large number of companies that sought to harness these recent innovations in developing a new generation of aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] During early 1954, the company embarked on a private study into a conceptual carrier-based, long-range, all-weather strike bomber, that would be capable of supersonic speeds while carrying a sizable payload.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] This aircraft was envisioned as a successor to the abortive North American XA2J Super Savage.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Much of this early work was undertaken by NAA's recently acquired Columbus division, overseen by chief of preliminary design Frank G.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] During the mid-1950s, the notion of a nuclear-armed aircraft capable of speeds of up to Mach 2 was considered to be quite ambitious, and only more so for that same aircraft to be operable under the unavoidable constraints imposed by aircraft carrier operations.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] In terms of its basic configuration, the conceptual aircraft featured twin-engines and high-mounted wing, as did the XA2J, but differed substantially by being highly swept and adopting jet propulsion.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] According to aviation authors Bill Gunston and Peter Gilchrist, NAA's design incorporated numerous advanced technology features, such as being the first supersonic bomber to be designed with a slim forward fuselage, as well as being the first with fully-variable wedge-type side air intakes.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The company's preliminary design studies had been typically centered around a twin vertical fin/rudder arrangement, but this was substituted for a single large all-moving vertical fin as design definition proceeded.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] This proposal, which was referred to the *North American General Purpose Attack Weapon* (NAGPAW) concept, was promptly evaluated by the United States Navy.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The service produced numerous challenging demands, including the somewhat contradictory necessity of both a high speed of Mach 2 and the ability to take off from an aircraft carrier at maximum weight with no head-wind, also known as wind-over-the-deck, to assist the take-off.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Compton's team were able to reconcile these performance requirements into the design.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Following these changes, US Navy officials voiced their approval of the design and advocated for its procurement.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] During July 1955, an initial design contract, which included the production of a mockup, was issued to NAA.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] During September 1956, a follow-on contract for the production of a pair of flight-worthy prototypes, was awarded to the firm.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] On 31 August 1958, one of these prototypes performed the type's maiden flight from Columbus, Ohio.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] By this point, the role envisioned for the aircraft within the US Navy had shifted somewhat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Thus, the design team implemented a somewhat unorthodox bomb bay as to accommodate the stowage of a nuclear weapon, which was also designed to accommodate both fuel tanks and reconnaissance payloads.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] During the late 1950s and early 1960s, NAA worked on an improved bomber model, designated *A-5B*.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] This took advantage of the zero-wind requirement's elimination to considerably increase the aircraft's maximum weight, the fuselage being redesigned with a hump back to accommodate additional fuel.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The wings were also redesigned with enlarged trailing-edge flaps and fully-blown flaps; these changes, when carrying four external drop tanks, roughly doubled the bomber's range.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Development was halted after only six A-5Bs had been completed due to a shift in the US Navy's strategic focus that placed less value on manned bombers.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The majority of Vigilantes were of a reconnaissance configuration, designated *RA-5C*.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] It had a slightly greater wing area and added a long canoe-shaped fairing under the fuselage for a multi-sensor reconnaissance pack, which housed an APD-7 side-looking airborne radar (SLAR), AAS-21 infrared line scanner, and camera packs, as well as improved electronic countermeasures.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] An AN/ALQ-61 electronic intelligence system could also be carried.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The RA-5C retained the AN/ASB-12 bombing system, and could, in theory, carry weapons, although it never did in service.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Later-build RA-5Cs had more powerful J79-10 engines with afterburning thrust of 17,900 lbf (80 kN).
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The reconnaissance Vigilante weighed almost five tons more than the strike version with almost the same thrust and an only modestly enlarged wing, resulting in reduced acceleration and climb rate, though it remained fast in level flight.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF) considered acquiring the RA-5C as its principal bomber to succeed its fleet of English Electric Canberras.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Various other aircraft, such as the McDonnell F-4C/RF-4C, Dassault Mirage IVA, and the BAC TSR-2 were also considered for the role.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] However, the General Dynamics F-111C, a variant of the TFX (F-111) tailored to fulfil the requirements of the RAAF, was procured to meet the service's needs instead.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Due to the F-111C's protracted development, a team of RAAF officers advocated for an interim fleet of 36 Vigilantes to be acquired by the RAAF, having determined that the aircraft satisfied the service's requirements and could be delivered within a shorter time frame.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The Australian Government rejected this advice and no such procurement occurred.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The North American A-5 Vigilante was a supersonic carrier-based bomber.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] At the time of its introduction, the Vigilante was one of the largest and by far the most complex aircraft to operate from an aircraft carrier.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] It was furnished with a high-mounted swept wing with a boundary-layer control system (blown flaps) to improve low-speed lift.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] It lacked ailerons; instead, roll control was provided by spoilers in conjunction with differential deflection of the all-moving tail surfaces, which were paired with a relatively large all-moving single vertical stabilizer.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The use of aluminum-lithium alloy for wing skins and titanium for critical structures was also unusual for the era; other exotic materials included the use of a gold coating to reflect heat in key areas such as the bomb bay.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The wings, vertical stabilizer and the nose radome all folded to enable easier stowage onboard aircraft carriers.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Two widely spaced General Electric J79 turbojet engines were supplied with air through inlets with variable intake ramps.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] While the same engine was used by several other US military aircraft, such as the Convair B-58 Hustler and the McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II, the powerplants used on the A-5 differed in some ways, such as the use of a somewhat uncommon air-impingement starter along with a single igniter.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Both engines were equipped with constant-speed drives for alternators to generate a steady 30 kVA for the onboard electrical systems, a hydraulically-driven emergency supply generated by a ram air turbine was also installed.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The visibly slanted intake design was first used on the A-5 Vigilante but later become commonplace on military aircraft such the Tupolev Tu-22 bomber, Grumman F-14 Tomcat, MiG-25 and McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle fighter aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The electronics of the Vigilante were relatively advanced and complex at the time of its entry to service.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] It incorporated one of the first "fly-by-wire" systems on an operational aircraft, along with mechanical/hydraulic backup.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The Vigilante was the first bomber to feature a digital computer.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] It was operated by a crew of two, a pilot and a bombardier-navigator (BN), that were seated in tandem; both were provided with North American HS-1A ejection seats.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] On the reconnaissance variant, the bombardier-navigator was replaced by a reconnaissance/attack navigator (RAN).
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Given its original design as a carrier-based, supersonic, nuclear heavy attack aircraft, the Vigilante's main armament was carried in an unusual "linear bomb bay" between the engines in the rear fuselage, which allowed the bomb to be dropped at supersonic speeds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The single nuclear weapon, commonly the Mk 28 bomb, was attached to two disposable fuel tanks in the cylindrical bay in an assembly known as the "stores train".
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] A set of extendable fins was attached to the aft end of the most rearward fuel tank.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] These fuel tanks were to be emptied during the flight to the target and then jettisoned with the bomb by an explosive drogue gun.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The stores train was propelled rearward at about 50 feet per second (30 kn) relative to the aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] In practice, the system was not reliable and no live weapons were ever carried in the linear bomb bay.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] In the RA-5C configuration, the bay was used solely to accommodate fuel.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] On three occasions, the shock of the catapult launch caused the fuel cans to eject onto the deck; this phenomenon reportedly resulted in one aircraft loss.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Early production Vigilante were fitted with a pair of wing pylons, which were intended primarily for drop tanks.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The second Vigilante variant, the *A3J-2* (*A-5B*), featured two additional wing hardpoints, for a total of four, and also incorporated internal tanks for an additional 460 US gallons (1,700 L) of fuel (which added a pronounced dorsal "hump").
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] In practice, these hardpoints were rarely used.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Other improvements to the type included blown flaps on the leading edge of the wing and stronger landing gear.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] While designated by the US Navy as a "heavy" aircraft, the A-5 was surprisingly agile; without the drag of bombs or missiles, even escorting fighters found that the clean airframe and powerful engines made the Vigilante very fast at high and low altitudes.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] However, its high approach speed and high angle of attack contributed to a high workload during carrier landings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Designated *A3J-1*, the Vigilante first entered service with Heavy Attack Squadron Three (VAH-3) in June 1961 at Naval Air Station Sanford, Florida, replacing the Douglas A-3 Skywarrior in the heavy attack, e.g., "strategic nuclear strike" role.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] All variants of the Vigilante were built at North American Aviation's facility at Port Columbus Airport in Columbus, Ohio, alongside the North American T-2 Buckeye, T-39 Sabreliner and OV-10 Bronco.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Under the Tri-Services Designation plan implemented under Robert McNamara in September 1962, the Vigilante was redesignated *A-5*, with the initial A3J-1 becoming *A-5A* and the updated A3J-2 becoming *A-5B*.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The subsequent reconnaissance version, originally *A3J-3P*, became the *RA-5C*.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The Vigilante's early service proved troublesome, with many teething problems for its advanced systems.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Although these systems were highly sophisticated, the technology was in its infancy and its reliability was poor.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Although most of these reliability issues were eventually worked out as maintenance personnel gained greater experience with supporting these systems, the aircraft tended to remain a maintenance-intensive platform throughout its career.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] As a result, in 1963, procurement of the A-5 was ended and the type was converted to the fast reconnaissance role.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The first RA-5Cs were delivered to VAH-3, the A-5A and A-5B Replacement Air Group (RAG)/Fleet Replacement Squadron (FRS), subsequently redesignated as Reconnaissance Attack Squadron Three (RVAH-3), at Naval Air Station Sanford, Florida in July 1963.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] As they transitioned from the attack version to the reconnaissance version, all Vigilante squadrons were subsequently redesignated from VAH to RVAH.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Under Commander, Reconnaissance Attack Wing One (COMRECONATKWING ONE), a total of 10 RA-5C squadrons were ultimately established.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Kennedy* and *Nimitz* to the Atlantic, Mediterranean and Western Pacific.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Eight of ten squadrons of RA-5C Vigilantes also saw extensive service in the Vietnam War starting in August 1964, carrying out hazardous medium-level post-strike reconnaissance missions.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Although it proved fast and agile, 18 RA-5Cs were lost in combat: 14 to anti-aircraft fire, 3 to surface-to-air missiles, and 1 to a MiG-21 during Operation Linebacker II.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Nine more RA-5Cs were lost in operational accidents while serving with Task Force 77.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Due, in part, to these combat losses, 36 additional RA-5C aircraft were built from 1968 to 1970 as attrition replacements.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The tenant SAC bomb wing was then inactivated and control of Turner AFB was transferred from the Air Force to the Navy with the installation renamed Naval Air Station Albany.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] In 1974, after barely six years of service as a naval air station, Congress opted to close Naval Air Station Albany as part of a post-Vietnam force reduction, transferring all RA-5C units and personnel to Naval Air Station Key West, Florida.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] With the end of the Vietnam War, disestablishment of RVAH squadrons began in 1974, with the last Vigilante squadron, RVAH-7, completing its final deployment to the Western Pacific aboard USS *Ranger* in late 1979.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The final flight by an RA-5C took place on 20 November 1979 when a Vigilante departed Naval Air Station Key West, Florida.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Reconnaissance Attack Wing One was subsequently disestablished at Naval Air Station Key West in January 1980.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The Vigilante did not end the career of the A-3 Skywarrior, which would carry on as photo reconnaissance aircraft, electronic warfare platforms, aerial refueling tankers, and executive transport aircraft designated as RA-3A/B, EA-3A/B, ERA-3B, EKA-3B, KA-3B, and VA-3B, into the early 1990s.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Fighters replaced the RA-5C in the carrier-based reconnaissance role.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The RF-8G version of the Vought F-8 Crusader, modified with internal cameras, had already been serving in two light photographic squadrons (VFP-62 and VFP-63) since the early 1960s, operating from older aircraft carriers unable to support the Vigilante.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The Marine Corps' sole photographic squadron (VMFP-3) would also deploy aboard aircraft carriers during this period with RF-4B Phantom II aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] These squadrons superseded the Vigilante's role by providing detachments from the primary squadron to carrier air wings throughout the late 1970s and early-to-mid-1980s, until the transfer of the recon mission to the Navy's fighter squadron (VF) community operating the F-14 Tomcat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Select models of the F-14 Tomcat would eventually carry the multi-sensor Tactical Airborne Reconnaissance Pod System (TARPS) and the Digital Tactical Air Reconnaissance Pod (D-TARPS).
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Up to present day, the weight of carrier-based fighters such as the F-14 Tomcat and Boeing F/A-18E/F Super Hornet have evolved into the same 62,950 lb (28,550 kg) class as the Vigilante.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] On 13 December 1960, Navy Commander Leroy A.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Heath (pilot) and Lieutenant Larry Monroe (bombardier/navigator) established a world altitude record of 91,450.8 feet (27,874.2 m) in an A3J Vigilante carrying a 2,200-pound (1,000 kg) payload, beating the previous record by over 4 miles (6.4 km).
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] This new record held for more than 13 years.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The attempt was accomplished by reaching a speed of Mach 2.1, then pulling up to create a ballistic trajectory beyond the altitude at which its wings could continue to function.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] The engines flamed out in the thin atmosphere, and the aircraft rolled onto its back.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] This had already been experienced in previous flights, and so the pilot simply released the controls and the aircraft regained control naturally as it descended back into the thicker air of the lower atmosphere.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] (NA247) Prototypes, two built, one converted to RA-5C, one crashed 1959.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] 58 built, 6 cancelled, survivors re-designated A-5A in 1962, 42 converted to RA-5C.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Another variant with variable geometry wings and canards was proposed.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] 18 built, redesignated A-5B, 5 completed as XA3J-3P (YA-5C), all converted to RA-5C.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] 5 A3J-2s completed without reconnaissance systems and assigned to pilot familiarization, later converted to RA-5C.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Air Force variant in 1958 with an XLR46-NA-2 rocket engine installed in the linear bomb bay.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] Proposed Improved Manned Interceptor for U.S.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] An additional example of an A-5A destined for restoration as a museum aircraft, BuNo 146698, was destroyed when it was being relocated by Army helicopter from Naval Air Engineering Station Lakehurst, New Jersey to a new location.
[src:propelling-nozzle/a-5-vigilante] When the A-5A became unstable in flight, the helicopter crew was forced to jettison the aircraft from altitude.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:propelling-nozzle/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:propelling-nozzle/adiabatic-expansion] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:propelling-nozzle/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:propelling-nozzle/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:propelling-nozzle/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] A **propelling nozzle** or **exhaust ejector** is a nozzle that converts the internal energy of a working gas into propulsive force; it is the nozzle, which forms a jet, that separates a gas turbine, or gas generator, from a jet engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Propelling nozzles accelerate the available gas to subsonic, transonic, or supersonic velocities depending on the power setting of the engine, their internal shape and the pressures at entry to, and exit from, the nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The internal shape may be convergent or convergent-divergent (C-D).
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] C-D nozzles can accelerate the jet to supersonic velocities within the divergent section, whereas a convergent nozzle cannot accelerate the jet beyond sonic speed.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Propelling nozzles may have a fixed geometry, or they may have variable geometry to give different exit areas to control the operation of the engine when equipped with an afterburner or a reheat system.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] When afterburning engines are equipped with a C-D nozzle the throat area is variable.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Nozzles for supersonic flight speeds, at which high nozzle pressure ratios are generated, also have variable area divergent sections.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Turbofan engines may have an additional and separate propelling nozzle which further accelerates the bypass air.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Propelling nozzles also act as downstream restrictors, the consequences of which constitute an important aspect of engine design.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Convergent nozzles are used on many jet engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] If the nozzle pressure ratio is above the critical value (about 1.8:1) a convergent nozzle will choke, resulting in some of the expansion to atmospheric pressure taking place downstream of the throat (i.e., smallest flow area), in the jet wake.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Although jet momentum still produces much of the gross thrust, the imbalance between the throat static pressure and atmospheric pressure still generates some (pressure) thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Engines capable of supersonic flight have convergent-divergent exhaust duct features to generate supersonic flow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Rocket engines — the extreme case — owe their distinctive shape to the very high area ratios of their nozzles.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] When the pressure ratio across a convergent nozzle exceeds a critical value, the flow chokes, and thus the pressure of the exhaust exiting the engine exceeds the pressure of the surrounding air and cannot decrease via the conventional Venturi effect.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] This reduces the thrust producing efficiency of the nozzle by causing much of the expansion to take place downstream of the nozzle itself.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Consequently, rocket engines and jet engines for supersonic flight incorporate a C-D nozzle which permits further expansion against the inside of the nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] However, unlike the *fixed* convergent-divergent nozzle used on a conventional rocket motor, those on turbojet engines must have heavy and expensive variable geometry to cope with the great variation in nozzle pressure ratio that occurs with speeds from subsonic to over Mach 3.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Nonetheless, low area ratio nozzles have subsonic applications.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Non-afterburning subsonic engines have nozzles of a fixed size because the changes in engine performance with altitude and subsonic flight speeds are acceptable with a fixed nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] This is not the case at supersonic speeds as described for Concorde below.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] At the other extreme, some high bypass ratio civil turbofans control the fan working line by using a convergent-divergent nozzle with an extremely low (less than 1.01) area ratio on the bypass (or mixed exhaust) stream.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] At low airspeeds, such a setup causes the nozzle to act as if it had variable geometry by preventing it from choking and allowing it to accelerate and decelerate exhaust gas approaching the throat and divergent section, respectively.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Consequently, the nozzle exit area controls the fan match, which, being larger than the throat, pulls the fan working line slightly away from surge.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] At higher flight speeds, the ram rise in the intake chokes the throat and causes the nozzle's area to dictate the fan match; the nozzle, being smaller than the exit, causes the throat to push the fan working line slightly toward surge.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] This is not a problem, however, for a fan's surge margin is much greater at high flight speeds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Rocket motors also employ convergent-divergent nozzles, but these are usually of fixed geometry, to minimize weight.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Because of the high pressure ratios associated with rocket flight, rocket motor convergent-divergent nozzles have a much greater area ratio (exit/throat) than those fitted to jet engines.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The afterburners on combat aircraft require a bigger nozzle to prevent adversely affecting the operation of the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The variable area iris nozzle consists of a series of moving, overlapping petals with a nearly circular nozzle cross-section and is convergent to control the operation of the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Early afterburners were either on or off and used a 2-position clamshell, or eyelid, nozzle which gave only one area available for afterburning use.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Ejector refers to the pumping action of the very hot, high speed, engine exhaust entraining (ejecting) a surrounding airflow which, together with the internal geometry of the secondary, or diverging, nozzle controls the expansion of the engine exhaust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] At subsonic speeds, the airflow constricts the exhaust to a convergent shape.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] When afterburning is selected and the aircraft speeds up, the two nozzles dilate, which allows the exhaust to form a convergent-divergent shape, speeding the exhaust gasses past Mach 1.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] More complex engine installations use a tertiary airflow to reduce exit area at low speeds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Advantages of the ejector nozzle are relative simplicity and reliability in cases where the secondary nozzle flaps are positioned by pressure forces.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The ejector nozzle is also able to use air which has been ingested by the intake but which is not required by the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The amount of this air varies significantly across the flight envelope and ejector nozzles are well suited to matching the airflow between the intake system and engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Efficient use of this air in the nozzle was a prime requirement for aircraft that had to cruise efficiently at high supersonic speeds for prolonged periods, hence its use in the SR-71, Concorde and XB-70 Valkyrie.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] A simple example of ejector nozzle is the fixed geometry cylindrical shroud surrounding the afterburning nozzle on the J85 installation in the T-38 Talon.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] More complex were the arrangements used for the J58 (SR-71) and TF-30 (F-111) installations.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] They both used tertiary blow-in doors (open at lower speeds) and free-floating overlapping flaps for a final nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Both the blow-in doors and the final nozzle flaps are positioned by a balance of internal pressure from the engine exhaust and external pressure from the aircraft flowfield.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] On early J79 installations (F-104, F-4, A-5 Vigilante), actuation of the secondary nozzle was mechanically linked to the afterburner nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Later installations had the final nozzle mechanically actuated separately from the afterburner nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] This gave improved efficiency (better match of primary/secondary exit area with high Mach number requirement) at Mach 2 (B-58 Hustler) and Mach 3 (XB-70).
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Turbofan installations which do not require a secondary airflow to be pumped by the engine exhaust use the variable geometry C-D nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] These engines don't require the external cooling air needed by turbojets (hot afterburner casing).
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The divergent nozzle may be an integral part of the afterburner nozzle petal, an angled extension after the throat.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The petals travel along curved tracks and the axial translation and simultaneous rotation increases the throat area for afterburning, while the trailing portion becomes a divergence with bigger exit area for more complete expansion at higher speeds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The primary and secondary petals may be hinged together and actuated by the same mechanism to provide afterburner control and high nozzle pressure ratio expansion as on the EJ200 (Eurofighter).
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Other examples are found on the F-15, F-16, B-1B.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Nozzles for vectored thrust include fixed geometry Bristol Siddeley Pegasus and variable geometry F119 (F-22).
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The thrust reversers on some engines are incorporated into the nozzle itself and are known as target thrust reversers.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The nozzle opens up in two halves which come together to redirect the exhaust partially forward.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Since the nozzle area has an influence on the operation of the engine (see below), the deployed thrust reverser has to be spaced the correct distance from the jetpipe to prevent changes in engine operating limits.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Examples of target thrust reversers are found on the Fokker 100, Gulfstream IV and Dassault F7X.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Jet noise may be reduced by adding features to the exit of the nozzle which increase the surface area of the cylindrical jet.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Commercial turbojets and early by-pass engines typically split the jet into multiple lobes.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Modern high by-pass turbofans have triangular serrations, called chevrons, which protrude slightly into the propelling jet.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The nozzle, by virtue of setting the back-pressure, acts as a downstream restrictor to the compressor, and thus determines what goes into the front of the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] It shares this function with the other downstream restrictor, the turbine nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The areas of both the propelling nozzle and turbine nozzle set the mass flow through the engine and the maximum pressure.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] While both these areas are fixed in many engines (i.e. those with a simple fixed propelling nozzle), others, most notably those with afterburning, have a variable area propelling nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] This area variation is necessary to contain the disturbing effect on the engine of the high combustion temperatures in the jet pipe, though the area may also be varied during non-afterburning operation to alter the pumping performance of the compressor at lower thrust settings.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] For example, if the propelling nozzle were to be removed to convert a turbojet into a turboshaft, the role played by the nozzle area is now taken by the area of the power turbine nozzle guide vanes or stators.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Overexpansion occurs when the exit area is too big relative to the size of the afterburner, or primary, nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] This occurred under certain conditions on the J85 installation in the T-38.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The secondary or final nozzle was a fixed geometry sized for the maximum afterburner case.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] At non-afterburner thrust settings the exit area was too big for the closed engine nozzle giving over-expansion.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Free-floating doors were added to the ejector allowing secondary air to control the primary jet expansion.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] For complete expansion to ambient pressure, and hence maximum nozzle thrust or efficiency, the required area ratio increases with flight Mach number.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Beyond this point the nozzle diameter becomes the biggest diameter and starts to incur increasing drag.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Nozzles are thus limited to the installation size and the loss in thrust incurred is a trade off with other considerations such as lower drag, less weight.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Examples are the F-16 at Mach 2.0 and the XB-70 at Mach 3.0.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Another consideration may relate to the required nozzle cooling flow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The divergent flaps or petals have to be isolated from the afterburner flame temperature, which may be of the order of 3,600 °F (1,980 °C), by a layer of cooling air.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] A longer divergence means more area to be cooled.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The thrust loss from incomplete expansion is traded against the benefits of less cooling flow.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] This applied to the TF-30 nozzle in the F-14A where the ideal area ratio at Mach 2.4 was limited to a lower value.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] A divergent section gives added exhaust velocity and hence thrust at supersonic flight speeds.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The effect of adding a divergent section was demonstrated with Pratt & Whitney's first C-D nozzle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The convergent nozzle was replaced with a C-D nozzle on the same engine J57 in the same aircraft F-101.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The increased thrust from the C-D nozzle (2,000 lb, 910 kg at sea-level take-off) on this engine raised the speed from Mach 1.6 to almost 2.0 enabling the Air Force to set a world's speed record of 1,207.6 mph (1,943.4 km/h) which was just below Mach 2 for the temperature on that day.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The true worth of the C-D nozzle was not realised on the F-101 as the intake was not modified for the higher speeds attainable.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Another example was the replacement of a convergent with a C-D nozzle on the YF-106/P&W J75 when it would not quite reach Mach 2.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Together with the introduction of the C-D nozzle, the inlet was redesigned.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The USAF subsequently set a world's speed record with the F-106 of 1526 mph (Mach 2.43).
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Some very early jet engines that were not equipped with an afterburner, such as the BMW 003 and the Jumo 004 (which had a design ), had a variable area nozzle formed by a translating plug known as a *Zwiebel* [wild onion] from its shape.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The Jumo 004 had a large area for starting to prevent overheating the turbine and a smaller area for take-off and flight to give higher exhaust velocity and thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The 004's *Zwiebel* possessed a 40 cm (16 in) range of forward/reverse travel to vary the exhaust nozzle area, driven by an electric motor-driven mechanism within the body's divergent area just behind the turbine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Afterburner-equipped engines may also open the nozzle for starting and at idle.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The idle thrust is reduced which lowers taxi speeds and brake wear.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] This feature on the J75 engine in the F-106 was called 'Idle Thrust Control' and reduced idle thrust by 40%.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] On aircraft carriers, lower idle thrust reduces the hazards from jet blast.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] In some applications, such as the J79 installation in various aircraft, during fast throttle advances, the nozzle area may be prevented from closing beyond a certain point to allow a more rapid increase in RPM and hence faster time to maximum thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] On some augmented turbofans the fan operating line is controlled with nozzle area during both dry and wet operation to trade excess surge margin for more thrust.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] The nozzle area is increased during afterburner operation to limit the upstream effects on the engine.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] To run a turbofan to give maximum airflow (thrust), the nozzle area may be controlled to keep the fan operating line in its optimum position.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] For a turbojet to give maximum thrust, the area may be controlled to keep the turbine exhaust temperature at its limit.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] In early afterburner installations, the pilot had to check the nozzle position indicator after selecting afterburner.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] If the nozzle did not open for some reason, and the pilot did not react by cancelling the afterburner selection, typical controls of that period (e.g. the J47 in the F-86L), could cause the turbine blades to overheat and fail.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] Certain aircraft, like the German Bf 109 and the Macchi C.202/205 were fitted with "ejector-type exhausts".
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] These exhausts converted some of the waste energy of the (internal combustion) engines exhaust-flow into a small amount of forward thrust by accelerating the hot gasses in a rearward direction to a speed greater than that of the aircraft.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] All exhaust configurations do this to some extent if the exhaust gasses are discharged in a rearward direction.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] A particular thrust-producing exhaust device was patented by Rolls-Royce Limited in 1937.
[src:propelling-nozzle/propelling-nozzle] On the 1944 de Havilland Hornet's Rolls-Royce Merlin 130/131 engines the thrust from the multi-ejector exhausts were equivalent to an extra 70bhp per-engine at full-throttle height.
